      <text xml:space="preserve" bytes="926">{{Unreferenced|date=March 2007}}
A '''dirty subsidy''' is a payment or incentive by a [[government]] to a private [[corporation]] (or another level of government) that encourages [[waste]] of raw materials, [[natural resources]], or [[energy]], or results in [[pollution]] or other human health hazards.

[[Green economics]] often focuses on the impact of eliminating such subsidies, and implementing what is sometimes called '''full cost accounting''' although the notion of a &quot;cost&quot; is so political as to render this phrase almost meaningless.  [[Green politics]] focuses on actually eliminating the subsidies by seeking change to [[agricultural policy]] and [[industrial policy]], as well as [[tax, tariff and trade]] rules that favor imports from jurisdictions that offer such subsidies. 

